  "What is a nonrenewable resource?": "",
  "A resource that can be regrown every season": "",
  "A resource produced by photosynthesis": "",
  "Any resource that comes from the ocean": "",
  "A resource that exists in fixed quantities and cannot be replenished on a human timescale": "",
  "Nonrenewable resources such as fossil fuels and mineral ores exist in finite amounts because they formed over geological timescales far exceeding a human lifetime.": "",
  "What is sustainability in the context of resource use?": "",
  "Meeting present needs without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs": "",
  "Relying solely on nonrenewable resources": "",
  "Eliminating all use of natural resources": "",
  "Using resources as quickly as possible to maximize economic growth": "",
  "Sustainability, as defined by the Brundtland Commission in 1987, refers to using resources at a rate that allows natural systems to replenish them, ensuring long-term availability for future generations.": "",
  "What is resource depletion?": "",
  "The consumption of a resource faster than it can be replenished, leading to diminished supply": "",
  "The process of converting renewable resources into nonrenewable ones": "",
  "The discovery of new resource deposits": "",
  "Recycling resources to extend their use": "",
  "Resource depletion occurs when the rate of extraction or consumption exceeds the rate of natural replenishment, ultimately reducing the total available stock of that resource.": "",
