  "The GDP of a country with abundant resources": "",
  "Natural capital includes Earth's natural resources such as minerals, water, and air, as well as ecosystem services like pollination, water purification, and climate regulation that sustain life and economic activity.": "",
  "A coastal community relies heavily on fishing for its economy. Over the past decade, fish populations have declined by 60% due to overharvesting. Which approach would best help this community manage its fishery sustainably?": "",
  "Implement catch limits, establish marine protected areas, and allow fish populations time to recover": "",
  "Build fish farms that release wastewater directly into the ocean": "",
  "Switch entirely to imported fish and abandon the local fishery": "",
  "Increase the number of fishing boats to catch the remaining fish before they disappear": "",
  "Sustainable fishery management combines catch limits to prevent overharvesting, marine protected areas where fish can reproduce undisturbed, and recovery periods to allow depleted populations to rebuild.": "",
  "A developing nation discovers a large deposit of rare earth minerals needed for electronics manufacturing. Environmental groups warn that mining could destroy a biodiverse rainforest. What does this situation best illustrate?": "",
  "The conflict between short-term economic gain from nonrenewable resource extraction and long-term ecological preservation": "",
  "That rare earth minerals are a renewable resource based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons, particularly regarding rainforest based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "That mining always benefits biodiversity when evaluated systematically": "",
  "This scenario highlights the fundamental tension between exploiting finite mineral resources for economic development and preserving irreplaceable ecosystems and biodiversity for long-term ecological health.": "",
  "A farmer in a semi-arid region is pumping groundwater from an aquifer at twice the rate it is being recharged by rainfall. If this practice continues, what is the most likely long-term consequence?": "",
